<div id="bookReviews">
  




  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_280313405" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/280313405" />
    <a title="Bart DePalma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7238611-bart-depalma"><img alt="Bart DePalma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442615040p2/7238611.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/280313405?book_show_action=true">Feb 19, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bart DePalma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bart DePalma" href="/user/show/7238611-bart-depalma">Bart DePalma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer280313405" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6524751801920131300">During what seems like a never ending Great Recession, Ronald Martin, Jr.&apos;s &quot;Prepare for the Worst and Pray for the Best&quot; is a unique and valuable self help book, alternatively dispensing advice to the individual trying to find their American Dream and then to the citizen trying to make sense of a political system that has seemingly gone mad. The author writes in a colloquial style that reminds me of my father&apos;s advice to me over the years.<br/><br/>Mr. Martin begins his book by hammering home the necessi</span>
  <span id="freeText6524751801920131300" style="display:none">During what seems like a never ending Great Recession, Ronald Martin, Jr.'s "Prepare for the Worst and Pray for the Best" is a unique and valuable self help book, alternatively dispensing advice to the individual trying to find their American Dream and then to the citizen trying to make sense of a political system that has seemingly gone mad. The author writes in a colloquial style that reminds me of my father's advice to me over the years.<br /><br />Mr. Martin begins his book by hammering home the necessity of obtaining an education to avoid poverty and then how to draft a resume and pitch yourself in a job interview. Helpful information for those about to enter or the unemployed attempting to re-enter the workforce.<br /><br />Then he pivots into a survey of the problems contributing to our Great Recession. I enjoyed the interesting asides informing the reader where to obtain free land to start up a small town business and the insane web of taxes most of us pay without realizing it.<br /><br />The next two chapters offer advice on balancing thrift and personal happiness to avoid the bad times, with a handy checklist of preparations in case the worse befalls you and your family. I had to smile as I recalled many of the same tips from my own dad.<br /><br />The author concludes with a survey of the political issues of our time, including the general positions of the political right and left, and then each major candidate in the 2012 elections, on each of those issues.<br /><br />Ron Martin intends "Prepare for the Worst and Pray for the Best" to be a book for a general audience. However, I would especially recommend giving this book to the young people in your life who are preparing to make their own way in the world and would especially benefit from Mr. Martin's advice.<br /><br />Bart DePalma<br />Author of Never Allow A Crisis To Go To Waste: Barack Obama and the Evolution of American Socialism</span>
  <a data-text-id="6524751801920131300" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

